   {:e #blake3 "7ff8ea684b462c2829fb98edb7a4d0f9db5ae7dfc8ea126e92eac680c21b186d" :a :db/ident :v :harvest/session-braid-user-1774310353 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "7ff8ea684b462c2829fb98edb7a4d0f9db5ae7dfc8ea126e92eac680c21b186d" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :recon/trace-9e24c9e29409936c; ADR-FOUNDATION-031: THE INTROSPECTIVE OBSERVER. The daemon is not a performance optimization — it is the mechanism that makes C7 (self-bootstrap) actually true. Without persistent identity, braid cannot observe itself. The daemon enables reflexive divergence detection (Type 9): system vs system's-model-of-itself. Three converging insights crystallize: (1) ADR-029 connections-as-datoms — runtime observations ARE datoms with the same 6 lifecycle attributes. The connection between routing-latency and store-size IS a knowledge relationship that strengthens through co-activation and calibrates through hypothesis outcomes. (2) ADR-030 free energy gradient — F(S) applied to braid's own runtime. The store IS Q(s), the project IS P(o,s), but braid's runtime is ALSO P(o,s). The daemon computes F(S) over itself. (3) FEGH bridge hypotheses apply reflexively — when the self-model has disconnected clusters, spectral partition proposes bridges: 'what connects store loading to routing computation?' THIS is the question that would have prevented today's misdiagnosis. The fixed point: the system learns about itself using the same epistemological machinery it uses to learn about everything else. Four levels of reflexive observation (agent->project, braid->project, daemon->braid, calibration->daemon), each using the same three primitives (morphisms, reconciliation, acquisition function), each producing datoms that feed the level above.; Session entity: :recon/trace-9108db33da524be0; Session entity: :recon/trace-e40f867b0efca8b2; Session entity: :recon/trace-0614511171463ae7; Session entity: :recon/trace-ef147549124d0081; Session entity: :task/t-99521e88; Session entity: :recon/trace-10ef55db3f942ae2; ARCHITECTURE: W-alpha (Working Set Alpha, INV-STORE-014) implementation for daemon. W-alpha is the private agent working set where runtime telemetry lives — NOT in the shared store. Rationale: runtime datoms are operational, not project knowledge; they would pollute CRDT merge with machine-specific data. Implementation: (1) Separate .braid/.walpha/ directory with its own txn files. (2) Daemon loads W-alpha at startup alongside the shared store. (3) Runtime datoms written to W-alpha only. (4) On harvest --commit, W-alpha is compacted (old entries pruned). (5) Boundaries can evaluate W-alpha datoms alongside shared store datoms. (6) W-alpha is NOT included in braid merge (not shared between agents/machines).; Session entity: :recon/trace-e366ec7d73bf5ee0; Session entity: :task/t-cd974c3c; Session entity: :recon/trace-c99353b6b86fb46c; Session entity: :recon/trace-d844521d3211eb72; ARCHITECTURE: Code-aware CRB enhancement. When braid task create runs CRB-PREVIEW, augment the Jaccard + VAET search with a codebase grep for related implementations. Sources: (1) Existing store datoms (current CRB). (2) :capability/* datoms from daemon census (new). (3) Direct codebase search: extract keywords from the task title, grep src/ for function names, struct names, and feature-related identifiers. Surface matches as 'related: [code] function_name in file.rs:line'. Threshold: score > 0.5 triggers WARNING: high-confidence code match. This prevents the duplicate-implementation failure mode we experienced (PERF-1 created when store.bin cache already existed).; HEBBIAN SELF-LEARNING: The daemon's runtime datoms form connections (ADR-029). When routing-latency and store-load-latency are measured in the same session, their connection's activation-count increments. When routing is cached and latency drops, the routing-latency -> cache-hit connection gets Hebbian boost. Over sessions, the daemon learns the CAUSAL STRUCTURE of its own performance: which components are bottlenecks, which caching strategies work, which boundaries are frequently violated. This learned causal model is the basis for reflexive bridge hypotheses (PERF-4b) — the spectral partition finds communities in the LEARNED causal graph, not just the raw measurement graph. The causal structure discovery uses the same three learning loops (calibration, structure, ontology) that the project knowledge uses. This is the deepest expression of C7: the system doesn't just learn — it learns the STRUCTURE OF ITS OWN LEARNING.; Session entity: :recon/trace-49f47a4e805916a8; Session entity: :recon/trace-54dd04bef853de2a; Session entity: :task/t-7f0ca8de; Session entity: :recon/trace-f4c127bd30add9ae; Session entity: :recon/trace-0d2e8ff24b562dad; LEVEL 4 MISSING: Learns to teach about itself. The seed (AGENTS.md injection) is a PROJECTION of the store into the agent's context window. The quality of that projection determines the next agent's effectiveness. Currently the seed uses a fixed template. What's missing: measuring seed quality from agent outcomes. The hypothesis: this seed will enable the next agent to complete task X. The outcome: the agent did/didn't complete X. The calibration: adjust which datoms are included in the seed. This is the system LEARNING HOW TO TEACH — optimizing the Markov blanket's ACTIVE states (seed = active state that shapes the next observer). Uses the existing hypothesis ledger. The prediction: seed including section Y leads to task completion rate Z. The measurement: actual completion rate. The adjustment: sections with low predictive value are demoted, high-value sections promoted. This is attention applied to the SEED, not just to context blocks.; Session entity: :recon/trace-babf4d0dd01a82e6; Session entity: :recon/trace-fbfbe64ed665c4d8; Session entity: :task/t-7aa2c3ae; SCHEMA-NEEDED: Layer 7 runtime schema for daemon self-model. Required attributes: :runtime/command (String, One) — command name. :runtime/latency-ms (Long, One) — wall-clock latency. :runtime/cache-hit (Boolean, One) — whether store cache hit. :runtime/routing-ms (Long, One) — routing computation time. :runtime/store-datom-count (Long, One) — datom count at measurement time. :runtime/error-count (Long, One) — errors this command. :runtime/timestamp (Instant, One). :capability/implemented (Boolean, One). :capability/file-path (String, One). :capability/line-range (String, One). :capability/subsystem (String, One). All runtime entities carry the 6 ADR-029 lifecycle attributes for connection tracking.; Session entity: :recon/trace-f4a942a58a91d9e4; Session entity: :recon/trace-af7c057e1db2fbf4; SPEC-NEEDED: INV-FOUNDATION-015 (Reflexive Divergence Detection) exists as observation but not as formal spec. The invariant requires: BoundaryRegistry MUST include at least one Reflexive boundary. Falsification: if braid claims capability X absent but binary implements X, OR if self-model claims latency T but measured latency >2T, the boundary is violated and F(S) must decrease.; Session entity: :task/t-3c27bfb1; Session entity: :recon/trace-7a732abfce68b80b; Session entity: :recon/trace-04dfc08b4e094d4f; Session entity: :recon/trace-7c5b59d3f894ecb4; Session entity: :task/t-7dffddd2; Session entity: :recon/trace-68476970042bf045; THE MARKOV BLANKET INSIGHT: The braid CLI is the Markov blanket between the internal model (store = Q(s) = project epistemology) and external reality (project/codebase = P(o,s)). Sensory states: observe, harvest, trace — observations flowing in. Active states: go, seed, guidance — actions flowing out. The daemon sits INSIDE the blanket and observes the blanket itself: how fast are observations flowing? How accurately do actions predict outcomes? Is the blanket thickening (latency) or thinning (efficiency)? This completes the free energy formalism: F = KL[Q||P] + E[-log P(o)]. Q = store, P = project, the Markov blanket = CLI, and the daemon = the system's awareness of its own blanket dynamics. The introspective observer doesn't add a new mechanism — it applies the EXISTING mechanism (observe-compare-reduce) to the boundary itself.; Session entity: :recon/trace-61c833cc29276b7d; Session entity: :task/t-2d765c94; Session entity: :recon/trace-c796ab314ee411d5; Session entity: :task/t-a1f1300a; Session entity: :recon/trace-ef7ed243854f6eb6; Session entity: :recon/trace-abe9d57e80a6da75; Session entity: :recon/trace-003e3777779aa116; Session entity: :recon/trace-d86393d27905c616; Session entity: :recon/trace-03b9e43d98b397ba; Session entity: :recon/trace-e7aaa6869d04ab62; Session entity: :task/t-7c01e013; Session entity: :recon/trace-7a8288489310d6ff; SPEC-NEEDED: ADR-FOUNDATION-031 (Introspective Observer) exists as observation but not as formal spec element. Must crystallize via braid spec create. The ADR establishes: (1) The daemon as the mechanism enabling C7 self-bootstrap via persistent identity. (2) Reflexive divergence (Type 9) as ninth entry in reconciliation taxonomy. (3) Runtime observations as datoms with ADR-029 lifecycle attributes. (4) The CLI as Markov blanket between Q(s)=store and P(o,s)=project. (5) Four levels of reflexive observation: agent->project, braid->project, daemon->braid, calibration->daemon. Each level uses the same three primitives.; THE COMPLETE ASSOCIATIVE SYSTEM. Three mechanisms, one knowledge graph, one acquisition function: (1) CRB (Crystallization Reconciliation Bridge) = recognition memory. Surfaces KNOWN connections on every transaction via Jaccard + VAET BFS. Already implemented, already runs on every observe/task create. Failed today because it only searches the STORE, not the CODE. (2) FEGH bridge hypotheses = creative inference. Surfaces MISSING connections via spectral partition of knowledge graph. Proposes bridges between disconnected communities. Not yet implemented. (3) Capability census = perception/grounding. Daemon scans binary at startup, populates :capability/* datoms. Grounds the store's model in the binary's reality. Fills the gap that caused today's failure. Together: perception (census) feeds recognition (CRB) feeds creativity (FEGH). All three use the same 6 ADR-029 lifecycle attributes. All three scored by alpha = E[delta-F(S)]/cost. All three produce datoms in the same knowledge graph. This IS how associative memory works: perceive, recognize, hypothesize — one network, one gradient, one learning dynamic. The daemon unifies all three by providing the persistent identity that makes continuous association possible.; Session entity: :recon/trace-00a48fe525de5a36; Session entity: :recon/trace-f658d593a0a80fe6; Session entity: :task/t-b38f580d; Session entity: :recon/trace-2b9cf0bb70f89b8c; Session entity: :recon/trace-502ad9c80d75910c; ARCHITECTURE: Incremental routing for daemon. When a new txn arrives, the daemon should NOT recompute all 256 task routings. Instead: (1) Identify AFFECTED entities: tasks whose deps, spec-refs, or boundaries intersect with the new txn's datom entities. (2) Re-score only those tasks (typically 1-5). (3) Re-sort the full routing list (O(N log N) sort is cheap). This reduces per-txn routing from O(N*D) to O(k*D) where k = affected tasks << N = total tasks. For a typical braid observe that adds 1 observation datom, k=0 (no tasks affected) and routing doesn't change at all. Algebraic property: incremental routing must produce the SAME result as full recomputation (determinism). Verify with proptest: for any txn sequence, incremental and full routing produce identical orderings.; Session entity: :recon/trace-e130fa87ff2655a1; Session entity: :recon/trace-f39fbd82d6002e13; CRITICAL DIAGNOSTIC: braid status 30s bottleneck is NOT store loading (store.bin cache already works, task list = 1.4s). The bottleneck is compute_routing_from_store called 3x per status, each O(tasks*datoms) = O(256*70K) ~ 10s. Three call sites: (1) compute_action_from_store in build_status_projection, (2) derive_actions in build_json, (3) compute_routing_from_store in build_verbose. Fix: PERF-2a deduplicates to 1 call (30s->12s), PERF-2b caches routing to disk (12s->2s on repeat), PERF-4 daemon keeps routing hot (<100ms).; Session entity: :recon/trace-bd42bcc11669cc46; Session entity: :recon/trace-446cc586224b4b90; Session entity: :task/t-00daed1d; Session entity: :recon/trace-cf94ede3e08572af; Session entity: :recon/trace-147388e46569b00d; DOG-FOOD VALIDATION PLAN: Two-phase validation after daemon+FEGH implementation. Phase A (Reflexive): Run daemon on braid's own 70K store. Verify: (1) Capability census detects all implemented features. (2) RuntimeBoundary fires on latency > 5s (if it would without daemon cache). (3) Reflexive FEGH generates the routing/caching bridge hypothesis. (4) The bridge is scored by alpha and ranks in top-3 recommendations. Acceptance: the system discovers the exact performance insight that took us 1 hour manually. Phase B (External): Re-run exploration agent on Go CLI project. Same protocol as Session 037 dog-food. Measure: exploration usefulness (target 7+/10, was 4/10). Compare: with and without bridge hypothesis suggestions. Record: all outcomes in hypothesis ledger. Calibrate: per-type accuracy for item_type=exploration.; Session entity: :task/t-c126acce; Session entity: :task/t-c0650b3c; INV-FOUNDATION-015: Reflexive Divergence Detection. The BoundaryRegistry MUST include at least one boundary of type Reflexive that evaluates the system's model of its own runtime against measured runtime behavior. Falsification: if braid's self-model claims capability X does not exist but the binary implements X, OR if the self-model claims operation Y takes T seconds but measured latency is >2T, the reflexive boundary is violated and F(S) must decrease. This is the ninth divergence type in the reconciliation taxonomy: system vs system's-own-model. Detection: daemon measures runtime datoms (latency, cache hits, computation costs). Resolution: daemon updates self-model datoms in W-alpha. Calibration: hypothesis ledger tracks predicted vs actual runtime performance.; Session entity: :task/t-e1310de6; Session entity: :recon/trace-cf081fc82346ec6b; Session entity: :task/t-5b3c0fb6; ARCHITECTURE: RuntimeBoundary type for BoundaryRegistry. A new boundary category that evaluates reflexive divergence (Type 9). Unlike existing boundaries that compare spec-to-impl, RuntimeBoundary compares self-model-to-measurement. Three initial boundaries: (1) latency-budget: status latency < configurable threshold (default 5s). Measured from :runtime/latency-ms in W-alpha. (2) cache-efficiency: cache hit rate > 0.8 across last 10 commands. Measured from :runtime/cache-hit in W-alpha. (3) computation-scaling: routing-ms should grow sublinearly with datom-count. If linear or superlinear, reflexive divergence. Implementation: BoundaryDef gains a RuntimeBoundaryConfig variant with data_source = W-alpha, metric = attribute keyword, threshold, comparison_op. evaluate_all checks runtime boundaries alongside structural boundaries.; Session entity: :recon/trace-8c243460e1418987; Session entity: :recon/trace-8665fb45f5cbea8b; Session entity: :recon/trace-60f8d4099ff917bd; Session entity: :task/t-034c8992; Session entity: :recon/trace-0e844f39d15d80dc; Session entity: :task/t-c0e8cbf8; Session entity: :task/t-308df6f1; MARKOV BLANKET DYNAMICS: The daemon observes not just runtime metrics but the FLOW properties of the blanket. Sensory bandwidth: observations per session, datoms per observation, entropy of observation categories. Active effectiveness: what fraction of guidance recommendations are followed? What fraction of seed sections are referenced? What fraction of task suggestions lead to completion? These FLOW metrics are the blanket dynamics that Friston's active inference framework uses to decide between model-update (perception) and world-update (action). High sensory bandwidth + low active effectiveness = the system knows a lot but can't guide effectively (increase action precision). Low sensory bandwidth + high active effectiveness = the system guides well but with limited knowledge (increase observation rate). The daemon tracks these to optimize the balance.\nSession entity: :task/t-59f761c3; Session entity: :task/t-b6350982; Session entity: :task/t-83d99b6b; Session entity: :task/t-56b8f57e; Session entity: :task/t-0986f448; Session entity: :task/t-30f5d046; Session entity: :task/t-52dad378; Session entity: :task/t-61db13f0; Session entity: :task/t-bad4f6ca" :op :assert}
